<div id="review_1618511769" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1618511769" />
    <a title="Adam Dalva" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3263980-adam-dalva"><img alt="Adam Dalva" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1452476649p2/3263980.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1618511769?book_show_action=true">Apr 23, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam Dalva" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam Dalva" href="/user/show/3263980-adam-dalva">Adam Dalva</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1618511769" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1196670568646274346">Extraordinary compendium of monologues detailing various effects of the Chernobyl disaster. Alexievich&apos;s skill at unearthing horrible, moving truths from her interviewees is notable. I&apos;d suggest supplementing the book with some background reading on Chernobyl (wikipedia is fine), since the medium doesn&apos;t allow for a direct re-telling of what happened. The two wives&apos; tales that bookend the narrative will stick with me for a long time.</span>
  <span id="freeText1196670568646274346" style="display:none">Extraordinary compendium of monologues detailing various effects of the Chernobyl disaster. Alexievich's skill at unearthing horrible, moving truths from her interviewees is notable. I'd suggest supplementing the book with some background reading on Chernobyl (wikipedia is fine), since the medium doesn't allow for a direct re-telling of what happened. The two wives' tales that bookend the narrative will stick with me for a long time.</span>
